[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(45) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Kept the ward.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—This should be read differently. The priests and Levites ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "kept the ward of their God, and the ward of purification, and the singers and porters,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " &c. To “keep the ward” is to observe the regular times and seasons of sacrifice and thanksgiving.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Nehemiah 12:45",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Nehemiah 12:45",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Both the singers and the porters kept the ward of their God — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That ward or charge which God had prescribed them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "in particular, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the charge of purification, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "of taking care that no unclean person or thing should enter into the house or courts of the Lord. Or, the meaning may be, the singers sung orderly in their courses, as they were appointed, and thereby ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "kept the ward of their God; and the porters kept the ward of the purification, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that is, duly observed the orders about it, in preventing the temple from being defiled by any unclean person or thing. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "According to the commandment of David and of Solomon his son — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who had regulated all things belonging to the duty of these persons.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "12:44-47 When the solemnities of a thanksgiving day leave such impressions on ministers and people, that both are more careful and cheerful in doing their duty, they are indeed acceptable to the Lord, and turn to good account. And whatever we do, must be purified by the blood of sprinkling, and by the grace of the Holy Spirit, or it cannot be acceptable to God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
